> I believe the way it works (though I could be wrong) is that an open-sour=
ce organization that signs up is supposed to have projects that concerns it=
s codebase or related components. That means either the toolchain or some r=
elated tool like a debugger or perhaps something like Merlin. Perhaps it co=
uld even extend to a library that can be shown to be extremely useful to th=
e community -- something like Lwt or Batteries.
>=20
> It would be harder to make the case for something that's purely an applic=
ation on top of OCaml, though I do believe that is possible once an organiz=
ation is more established with GSoC, for example Xen getting Mirage into GS=
oC -- Anil would probably know more about that kind of thing.
>=20
> Again, I could be wrong about this, so if anyone has better information, =
please correct me.
>=20
